{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653918"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18595"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18595"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.12,0.04,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79940"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11327"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5189"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79940"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMelatonin is a hormone that plays a crucial role in regulating sleep-wake cycles. Its production is closely linked to environmental light levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the synthesis of melatonin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conversion of serotonin to melatonin in the pineal gland","Conversion of tryptophan to melatonin in the hypothalamus","Production from dopamine in the retina","Secretion from the anterior pituitary gland","Synthesis from noradrenaline in the adrenal glands"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of serotonin to melatonin in the pineal gland\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct process. The pineal gland converts serotonin to N-acetylserotonin via N-acetyltransferase, which is then methylated by hydroxyindole-O-methyltransferase to form melatonin. This process is regulated by the suprachiasmatic nucleus, which receives light information from the retina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of tryptophan to melatonin in the hypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E - While tryptophan is a precursor to serotonin, melatonin synthesis occurs in the pineal gland, not the hypothalamus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction from dopamine in the retina\u003C/strong\u003E - The retina contains photoreceptors that detect light but does not synthesise significant amounts of melatonin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion from the anterior pituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E - The anterior pituitary produces several hormones but not melatonin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesis from noradrenaline in the adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E - The adrenal glands produce catecholamines but are not involved in melatonin synthesis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMelatonin production follows a circadian rhythm, with levels rising in darkness and falling with light exposure. This pattern helps regulate the sleep-wake cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Melatonin is primarily synthesised in the pineal gland from serotonin through a two-step enzymatic process.","Melatonin secretion follows a circadian rhythm with peak levels occurring during darkness.","Light 